to the "open" syscall then I get upset.<br /><br />Ehh.. They already are.<br /><br />And we _should_ expose to user space some way that files are linked. The<br />HFS behaviour where you cannot even tell whether it's a resource or<br />another filesystem that just happens to have that particular layout is not<br />giving people useful information.<br /><br />Quite frankly, "tar" is not that big a deal. It can be extended upon. I<br />don't see why people keep harping on that issue.<br /><br />I understand the "emulate the HFS layout on another filesystem for file<br />serving" gripe better, but I don't see that it is unreasonable to have a<br />HFS fileserver know whether the thing it is exporting is natively HFS or<br />not. The "regular filesystem emulation" might as well be done there,<br />instead of going the other way around.<br /><br />		Linus<br /><br /><br />-<br />To unsubscribe from this list: send the line "unsubscribe linux-kernel" in<br />the body of a message to majordomo&#64;vger.rutgers.edu<br />Please read the FAQ at <a href="http://www.tux.org/lkml/">http://www.tux.org/lkml/</a><br /><br /></pre><div align="center"><div class="shariff" data-services="[&quot;reddit&quot;]" data-theme="grey" data-lang="en" data-backend-url="//shariff.lkml.org/index.php"></div></div></td><td width="32" rowspan="2" class="c" valign="top"><img src="/images/icornerr.gif" width="32" height="32" alt="\" /></td></tr><tr><td align="right" valign="bottom">
